<tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Notation"><frontmatter> <anchor>9739</anchor> <addr>jms-000A</addr>  <route>jms-000A.xml</route> <date>January 18, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Kernel</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We will often write <tex>\operatorname{ker} {f} \xrightarrow{i _{ \operatorname{ker} { f } }} A</tex> for the <link href="jms-0009.xml" type="local" title="Kernel">kernel</link> of a map <tex>A \xrightarrow{f} B</tex> in a <link href="jms-000B.xml" type="local" title="Category with zero morphisms">category with zero morphisms</link> <tex>\mathcal{A}</tex>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>9741</anchor> <addr>jms-000B</addr>  <route>jms-000B.xml</route> <date>January 18, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Category with zero morphisms</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>category with zero morphisms</em> is defined to be a category <link href="jms-000H.xml" type="local" title="Enriched category">enriched</link> in the category of pointed sets and strict maps. The distinguished point of <tex>\mathbf{hom} _{ \mathcal{A} } { \left ( A , B \right )}</tex> shall be written <tex>0</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>9743</anchor> <addr>jms-0009</addr>  <route>jms-0009.xml</route> <date>January 18, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Kernel</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal{A}</tex> be a <link href="jms-000B.xml" type="local" title="Category with zero morphisms">category with zero morphisms</link>. Then the <em>kernel</em> of a morphism <tex>A \xrightarrow{f}  B</tex> in <tex>\mathcal{A}</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>K \xrightarrow</tex> such that for any <tex>X \xrightarrow{h} A</tex> with <tex>h;f=0</tex>, there exists a unique map <tex>X \xrightarrow K</tex>factoring <tex>X \xrightarrow{h} A</tex> through <tex>K \xrightarrow</tex> in the sense of the diagram below:</p><center><img src="resources/85e6e8d9bc0320178253421df5cbfe61-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>